document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Mathematics

BA5305E03BF3425191C2C010537BA6C6.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

578CD6BA87404ECB84B5AD84F919126A.description: Describe the whole as two halves or four fourths.

or half of or a fourth of.

D336179641B94847B523E7B15841E89C.description: Identify a whole partitioned into 2 or 4 equal shares.

6B081FED942F4436A36577B5AB38F579.description:

has been divided
into equal parts
(limit to half and
quarter).

Partition
rectangles into two
or four equal parts,

“halves,” “quarters,”
and whole.

rectangles into
two, three, or
four equal parts;
identify a part as
½, ¼, 1/3.

Partition shapes into
parts with equal areas.
Express the area of each part
as a unit fraction of the whole.
For example, partition a shape
into 4 parts with equal area,
and describe the area of each
part as 1/4 of the area of the
shape.

18445EDA120B4DF5BC2CDBD68F4173E4.description:
Interact with two- and three-dimensional objects in their
environment.

1DD7096380C3413781EB0F7D0962DA7C.description:

topic)

D7B67CDB360D4E89828F9940A9D1EB52.description:
Name shapes regardless of their orientations or overall
size.

Identify shapes as two-dimensional (lying in a plane, flat)
or three-dimensional (solid).

8D0D40868BD045838B922312BF9B386B.description:
Match
objects in the
environment
to their twodimensional shape
based on the
number of sides

stop sign in the
real world to an
octagon shape).

0954C3C84E564481BF04C4C45E2EC230.description:
Sort polygons
with up to 8 sides by
the number of sides
(Limit quadrilaterals to
rectangles, squares
and rhombuses).

E1B3A370287F4374814E3A4C47043667.description:
Sort
quadrilaterals
by the number
of sides and/
or the presence
or absence of
square corners
(right angles) (limit
quadrilaterals
to rectangles,
squares, and
rhombuses).

611A56CB9F1247EB86728FB93A6CBF82.description:
Draw and describe
triangles, quadrilaterals
(rhombuses, rectangles, and
squares), and polygons (up to
8 sides) based on the number
of sides and the presence or
absence of square corners
(right angles).

319A62060BAE417BA58EA7D1245B7DD9.description: Reason with shapes and their attributes.

topic)

Measure length and width with units and record the

F0A79D86514F42449898420F880BA9F8.description: Identify surfaces where a perimeter can be measured.

measurement

a rectangle
represented on a
grid.

Solve
addition or subtraction
measurement word
problems involving
perimeter.

91DB5B122A434EDFA32FFB6381BB1C43.description:
Solve
one-step
measurement
word problems
involving shapes
with the same
area and different
perimeters.

Solve real-world
and mathematical problems
involving perimeters of
polygons, including finding
the perimeter given the side
lengths, finding an unknown
side length, and exhibiting
rectangles with the same
perimeter and different areas
or with the same area and
different perimeters.

02B0F6C0D93E4140BD6B25E3CFD52F91.description: Geometric measurement: Recognize perimeter as an attribute of plane figures and distinguish between linear and area measures

956E020C7A8E4AF1A18CF38AA60BF31A.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

0A7140D5FACD48BD95DBC7745D6804A5.description: Arrange unit squares up to 20 into rows and columns.

52527AEF3A06483589BEF486B92A1BA5.description: Count unit squares up to 20 on a flat surface.

E62C32AA117740958FF27D1C45E1365D.description: Lay unit squares up to 20 on a flat surface.

7E798A8DADC747789E0AA3E19EAF3F4E.description: Identify surfaces where an area can be measured.

E0AC6804EA63421784EC29B3841EB5AC.description:
Use tiling
to cover the area
of a square and
count the tiles (unit
squares) to find
the area (whole
number factors
with areas limited
to 20).

FAE82AE8537C4997B93ECEDBA919D256.description:
Given a
visual model of a tiled
rectangle, identify
a number sentence
(repeated addition
or multiplication) that
represents a solution
for finding the area
(whole number factors
with areas limited to
30).

9C534C7BAB224840A3A038AD2688941B.description:
Given
the side length
measures for a
rectangle, find
the area (whole
number factors
with areas limited
to 40).

C8C0918ED37D4B20A18398982A36D238.description:
Relate area to the
operations of multiplication
and addition.
a. Find the area of a rectangle
with whole-number side
lengths by tiling it, and show
that the area is the same as
would be found by multiplying
the side lengths.
b. Multiply side lengths to
find areas of rectangles with
whole-number side lengths
in the context of solving
real-world and mathematical
problems, and represent
whole-number products
as rectangular areas in
mathematical reasoning.
c. Use tiling to show in a
concrete case that the area
of a rectangle with whole
number side lengths a and b
+ c is the sum of a × b and a
× c (represent the distributive
property with visual models
including an area model).
d. Recognize area as additive.
Find the area of figures
composed of rectangles
by decomposing into nonoverlapping rectangles and
adding the areas of the nonoverlapping parts, applying
this technique to solve realworld problems.

topic)

8868F7ECDAC94293830D7FFD89EADF0D.description:
Find the
area of rectangles
with whole-number
side lengths by
counting unit
squares (limit
factors of 1s, 2s,

up to 20).

478849E8900F4F9BA214653C091ABDC2.description:
Find the
area of rectangles
with whole-number
side lengths by

2s, 3s, 4s, 5s, and
10s with products not
exceeding 30).

487D0A460D6A450C8A2D98B52A2A5674.description:
Find the
area of rectangles
with whole-number
side lengths by
counting unit
squares (limit area
up to 40).

26069282CD034EF7AB03C7EBB8014D2F.description:
Measure areas by
counting unit squares (square
cm, square m, square in,
square ft, and improvised
units).

Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

E34952A84E714BD0A3D03FC4FD956114.description: Identify surfaces where an area can be measured.

122FF6FA49B44216A8328DE064E79793.description:
Understand that
the term “area”
is related to
measurement of a
surface.

62101E5F704449A58EC55CD16E7C66D9.description:
Understand
that an equal-sided
square can represent
1 unit of measure and
can be counted to
determine the area of
a plane figure.

A26217A3F25B45D78A68665EDD1261F1.description:
Recognize the
number of units
in a given surface
area represents an
array multiplication
problem.

99E567E84B974236AF50CA8E81FE8754.description:
Recognize area as an
attribute of plane figures and
understand concepts of area
measurement.
a. A square with side length 1
unit, called “a unit square,” is
said to have “one square unit”
of area, and can be used to
measure area.
b. A plane figure which can
be covered without gaps or
overlaps by n unit squares
is said to have an area of n
square units.

topic)

0C2296B3FBBD4AB9AB160234BAA3FAAE.description:

the number of same-size length units that span it with no
gaps or overlaps.

7883416AD6E24654B441EFB23FAC0B3C.description:
Express the length of an object as a whole number of
length units by laying multiple copies of a shorter object
(the length unit) end to end.

objects using a

objects using a
ruler to the nearest
fourth of an inch.

Generate
measurement data by
measuring lengths using
rulers marked with halves and
fourths of an inch. Show the
data by creating a line plot,
where the horizontal scale
is marked off in appropriate
units—whole numbers,
halves, or quarters.

Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

on a bar graph

sunny, cloudy,
rainy, snowy)

98A55C466B3B4C3C9865BD007F8CAA9F.description:
Identify
quantities from a
picture or bar graph
(e.g., in a class
graph representing
pets, represent 4
cats with 4 blocks or
4 cat pictures and
2 hamsters with 2
blocks or pictures).

A71ED0B0CFC54637B5AC05D00C0B6395.description:
Create
scaled bar (or
picture) graph from
given or collected
data sets and
interpret the graph,
including solving
1-step (e.g.,
“how many more”
“how many less”
problems).

7F26C43A132446329F0017953F9578DE.description:
Create scaled picture
graphs to represent a data
set with several categories.
Create scaled bar graphs
to represent a data set with
several categories. Solve twostep “how many more” and
“how many less” problems
using information presented
in the scaled graphs. For
example, create a bar graph
in which each square in the
bar graph might represent
5 pets, then determine how
many more/less in two given
categories.

C6D12893640C47B39051446A554F1815.description: Interact with measurement tools for volume and mass.

topic)

56DFA423854642F6B673302085A8C63B.description: Use different types of cups to measure volume of liquids.

Directly compare two beakers to see which one holds
more and which one holds less.

482A45A0A01B4883BAA883627E1FC6A3.description:
Directly compare two measuring cups to see which one
holds more and which one holds less.

52199F52F02A43A7A01E464E0DEA8D69.description:
Describe measurable attributes of a single object using
terms such as heavy/light.

48C2C4AB20DF41BAB96FDBD8C124E8EE.description:
Select the
appropriate tool to
measure volume
and mass (e.g.,
measuring cup,
scale).

3A922BDDE5DA42D082E852AA89290094.description:
Using
models and drawings,
measure and estimate
liquid volumes and
masses of objects
using standard units
of measure (e.g.,
measuring cup,
scale).

30367CE7031941CC8F0776A1151C16B6.description:
Solve
1-step word
problems involving
measures of liquid
volumes and
masses of objects
using standard
units of measure.

0B92FBF657244891B6C8B9D904B7D0FE.description:
Measure and estimate
liquid volumes and masses of
objects using standard units
of grams, kilograms, and
liters. Add, subtract, multiply,
or divide whole numbers
to solve one-step word
problems involving masses
or volumes that are given in
the same units, e.g., by using
drawings (such as a beaker
with a measurement scale)
to represent the problem.
Excludes multiplicative
comparison problems
involving notions of “times as
much”; see Table 2, page 96.

7BDC3F4644A849CE84D083F3729F91F7.description:
Interact with a clock and U.S. currency (pennies, nickels,
dimes, quarters, $1, $5, and $10).

topic)

4F4C1B176DD342CC825AD96218B68293.description: Find numerals on U.S. bills ($1, $5, and $10).

1D835A45115E469487D57F71D56B8BBE.description:
Read the hour hand on an analog clock at different times
of a day.

684D159A901F49DFAF04F30C90FC4C8B.description: Count to 12 using an analog clock.

12060DD18C2B456599C3A0A3DEFFCF02.description:
Know the meaning of the hour and the minute hands on
an analog clock.

0A683B4090DE4CDE875D20F15C9C3E18.description: Tell time using a digital clock.

0DE72B47B410476FA65DB8451B957A64.description:
Identify
and name all coins
and bills.

42A632D7FFD54DFEA715F5810B954E59.description:
Tell time
to the nearest hour
on an analog clock.
AND

CE3F7A2041C4418EA735932864EC0D40.description:
Identify,
name, and state
value for all coins and
bills (coins: pennies,
nickels, dimes,
quarters; bills: $1, $5,
$10, $20).

1DFE802DC78B4862874B97EFF539B253.description:
Tell time
to the nearest 30
minutes on an analog
clock.
AND

846A7DE3C45A4008A77AC083A041565F.description:
Name
and/or identify
equivalent
combinations of
coins and/or bills.

BF9D1C6735CC4265BA8B21C85FFDC349.description:
Tell time
to the nearest 15
minutes on an
analog clock.
AND

E89E25E4A8DA49DD8A16CB2561A1BDFF.description:
Work with time and
money.
a. Tell and write time to the
nearest minute. Measure time
intervals in minutes (within
90 minutes). Solve real-world
problems involving addition
and subtraction of time
intervals (elapsed time) in
minutes, e.g., by representing
the problem on a number line
diagram or clock.
b. Solve word problems
by adding and subtracting
within 1,000, dollars with
dollars and cents with cents
(not using dollars and cents
simultaneously) using the $
and ₵ symbol appropriately
(not including decimal
notation).

93A920905DDE427686F63320F8217D69.description: Solve problems involving money, measurement, and estimation of intervals of time, liquid volumes, and masses of objects.

76C9BB5A3CD74F79BCB89C0FED18E9F5.description:
Interact with area (rectangles) and length (number lines)
fraction models.

C9BD40F11B3047889FE90A020C7CF252.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

146C1EFF6D924AA49030E5885309E34D.description: Describe the whole as two halves or four fourths.

F3CDD730AE6B4536973939B3D87DAF7A.description:
Describe the equal shares of a whole as one half of or two
fourths of.

E1293E1C89A24E009F3C540E93E18E61.description:
Identify the same sized whole partitioned into 2 and 4
equal shares.

A6B7A46143924B8AA8A62F2F511CE093.description:
Identify
equivalent fractions
of ½ and ¼ when
represented with
visual fraction
models (e.g.
matching model
of ½ and 2/4 on a
number line).

236D1D4FFD984EBCA0F310C777C265A5.description:
Use visual
fraction models to
identify equivalent
fractions with
denominators of 2, 4,
6, and 8.

C0893C122ECE4418AD8050732BB8E0DE.description:
Use a
visual fraction
model to identify
greater than, less
than, and equal to
when comparing 2
fractions.

A673D01588E74074AB9CA6244F0974A9.description:
Explain equivalence
of fractions in special cases,
and compare fractions by
reasoning about their size.
a. Understand two fractions
as equivalent (equal) if they
are the same size or the same
point on a number line.
b. Recognize and generate
simple equivalent fractions,
e.g., 1/2 = 2/4, 4/6 = 2/3.
Explain why the fractions are
equivalent, e.g., by using a
visual fraction model.
c. Express whole numbers
as fractions, and recognize
fractions that are equivalent
to whole numbers. Examples:
Express 3 in the form 3 = 3/1;
recognize that 6/1 = 6; locate
4/4 and 1 at the same point of
a number line diagram.
d. Compare two fractions
with the same numerator or
the same denominator by
reasoning about their size.
Recognize that comparisons
are valid only when the two
fractions refer to the same
whole. Record the results of
comparisons with the symbols
>, =, or <, and justify the
conclusions, e.g., by using a
visual fraction model.

C46AA61CF35D483C97DA8AA917983FAB.description:
Interact with number lines with fractional unit markings of
¼ or ½.

B3530BE009524FAB8B35380958B6ADDA.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

161DF496FBC049768131EDA982CEF19B.description:
Identify a missing fraction on a number line marked with ¼
or ½ units up to 1.

3EDC858B0C9249CAB73BD646E754D0B8.description:
Identify the fractional markings on a number line marked
with fractions of ¼ or ½.

E2A706CEBBCF4C6297ADAC367367618E.description:
Know each marking on the number line represents a unit
fraction of ¼ or ½.

64DEDBCF38D042BC9CBEA4D5807DA9F0.description: Know what a number line is.

CDF513A094CF451B99820703F267EE75.description:
Identify
a fraction on
a number line
marked in equal
parts matching
the fraction
denominator (limit
to ½ and ¼).

0452BE0361794EDCB182F87D32927E41.description:
Identify
fraction(s) on a
number line marked in
equal parts matching
the fraction(s)’
denominator (limit to
denominators of 2, 3
and 4).

EDFE47DE75004B2C8CB02E4330AB7528.description:
Identify
fractions on a
number line
marked in equal
parts matching
the fraction
denominator (limit
to fractions with
denominators of 2,
3, 4, 6, 8).

FB1E3C2AE65D40289DAA1BA6470E4E18.description:
Understand a fraction
as a number on the number
line; represent fractions on a
number line diagram.
a. Represent a fraction 1/b
on a number line diagram
by defining the interval from
0 to 1 as the whole and
partitioning it into b equal
parts. Recognize that each
part has size 1/b and that the
endpoint of the part based at
0 locates the number 1/b on
the number line.
b. Represent a fraction a/b
(which may be greater than
1) on a number line diagram
by marking off a lengths 1/b
from 0. Recognize that the
resulting interval has size a/b
and that its endpoint locates
the number a/b on the number
line.

4962D4D661FD4DED9B282DDC02B25EB2.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

FB2DAEDA11674988979784D812442E6F.description: Describe the whole as two halves or four fourths.

D83ABC4C399A49C0A045FB3169D6AD56.description:
Describe the equal shares of a whole as halves or fourths,
or half of or a fourth of.

6D395DF34AA443C8B3766D2ED831D017.description: Identify a whole partitioned into 2 or 4 equal shares.

6A7C6E223983496BAB2E856805B0F249.description:
Identify a
unit fraction (1/4
or ½) as part of a
whole when shown
as a physical
and/or visual
representation.

68873E8E7AA14D91891D5A229F20CCDD.description:
Match
fractions with their
model (limit to 1/3,
2/3, ¼, ½, and 3/4).

7639C14BE06D43D48F5F9EEBDCD5BAA3.description:
Match
fractions with
their model (limit
to fractions with
denominators of 2,
3, 4, 6, 8).

7521F99AD1DD4A0BA89D4987263A3F78.description:
Understand a fraction
1/b as the quantity formed
by 1 part when a whole is
partitioned into b equal parts;
understand a fraction a/b as
the quantity formed by a parts
of size 1/b.

A459A317C4B94BF8B4D928C9889B49E9.description:
Develop understanding of fractions as numbers.
Grade 3 expectations in this domain are limited to fractions with denominators 2, 3, 4, 6, and 8.

252ADA59EDFF42698284E68456F22458.description:
Interact with physical objects (blocks) or drawings (100s
chart or multiplication chart).

872F31F72D164E7CA55CDA47392954B0.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

DF40462DDA404835B075DD0715A509E8.description:
Represent a number with a set of physical objects or a
drawing.

B7631613C7E447A39CDE05411EAACB7C.description:
Relate multiplication to repeated addition by writing a
number sentence.

278E8506352641D5AD26194219BB47A9.description: Know the symbols for multiplication (×) and equals (=).

When
shown a number
sentence of onedigit whole number
multiplied by 10,
match the product
to the number
sentence when
shown 2 possible
products (e.g.,
5x10= 50 or 80).

02993EE898484EE8A0AF9309EC0C2B55.description:
Multiply
one-digit whole
numbers by
multiples of 10
using visual
and/or physical
representation.

EB95D3D717034E8190969E62EFD54511.description:
Multiply one-digit
whole numbers by multiples
of 10 in the range of 10–90,
e.g., 9 × 80, 5 × 60, using
strategies based on place
value and properties of
operations.

BE1EBCB7CB44486A994053A58A037319.description:
Interact with physical objects (blocks) or drawings (may
include 100s chart) representing whole numbers within 20.

4F96A808F8664399986365A558F71725.description:
Engagement Statements (demonstration of engaged in the
topic)

6FACFACFA20746B7871024674AEC1529.description:
Add and subtract within 10 using strategies. Strategies
may include:
º Counting on
º Making ten (8 + 6 = 8 + 2 + 4 = 10 + 4 = 14)
º Decomposing a number leading to a ten (13 − 4 = 13
− 3 − 1 = 10 − 1 = 9)
º Using the relationship between addition and
subtraction; knowing that
º 8 + 4 = 12, one knows 12 − 8 = 4 and
º Creating equivalent but easier or known sums (adding
6 + 7 by creating the known equivalent 6 + 6 + 1 = 12
+ 1 = 13).
